<HEADLINE>
Basketball: Former NBA star Johnson dies at 52
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dennis Johnson, a guard who played on National Basketball
Association championship teams with the Boston Celtics and
Seattle Supersonics, died here Thursday at age 52.
</P>
<P>
Johnson was working as coach of the Austin Toros, a development
team for the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
A five-time NBA All-Star, Johnson played 1,100 NBA games over 14
seasons with the Celtics, Sonics and Phoenix Suns after being
selected in the second round of the 1976 NBA Draft by Seattle.
</P>
<P>
Johnson played four seasons for the Sonics, helping them win the
1979 NBA crown with 15.9 points and 4.7 rebounds a game and a
league-best defense. Johnson was named the 1979 NBA Finals Most
Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
He was traded to Phoenix in 1980 and spent three seasons with the
Suns before joining Boston in 1983.
</P>
<P>
The Celtics won two NBA crowns in his seven years at Boston,
taking the 1984 final over the Los Angeles Lakers in seven games
and the 1986 final over Houston in six games.
</P>
